Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document using the `tocindex` package:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocindex} % For automatic TOC generation with index entries

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section*{Introduction}
    \ subsection{Background}
        \ subsection{Motivation}
    \end{section*}

\section*{Chapter 1: Fundamentals}
    \subsection*{1.1.1 Basics}
        \subsection*{1.1.1.1 Key Concepts}
    \subsection*{1.2.2 Advanced Topics}
        \subsection*{1.2.2.1 New Developments}
    \end{section*}

\section*{Chapter 2: Specialized Topics}
    \subsection*{2.1.1 Advanced Techniques}
        \subsection*{2.1.1.1 Case Studies}
    \subsection*{2.2.2 Applications}
        \subsection*{2.2.2.1 Real-World Examples}
    \end{section*}

\section*{Chapter 3: Conclusion and Future Directions}
    \subsection*{3.1 Summary of Key Findings}
        \subsection*{3.1.1 Implications}
    \end{section*}

\clearpages
\cleaderspace
\tableofcontents

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- ** `\documentclass{article}`**: Specifies the document class.
- ** `\usepackage{tocindex}`**: Imports the `tocindex` package for automatic table of contents generation.
- ** `\tableofcontents`**: This command generates the TOC directly in the preamble, making it appear as a clickable link within the document.
- ** `\section*`, `\subsection*`**: These commands define the levels of headings for the TOC entries.
- ** `\clearpages`**: Clears any remaining page margins to ensure a clean appearance of the TOC.
- ** `\cleaderspace`**: Adds space before the TOC entry to maintain proper alignment.

This setup ensures that your document has a beautifully formatted TOC with links to each chapter, section, subsection, and subsubsection, making it easy to navigate through your document using the `tableofcontents` command.

